So as today is Inauguration Day and I am subsequently seeing my Twitter feed panic, here's the best advice I can give you all right now:
Find out who your representatives are in the House of Representatives and the Senates. Be aware of what legislation the gov't is pushing

RT @SimpsonsQOTD: ‚ÄúBut if it‚Äôs not Marge, then who is it? Where do I begin looking?‚Äù
‚ÄúThis really goes beyond my training as a furniture sa‚Ä¶
If you have a strong opinion either way about a piece of legislation, CALL them. Much more effective than emails, tweets, or sending letters
Emails can get deleted out of a politician's account. Letters can get thrown away. Tweets can get muted. Calls are still harder to ignore
I'm not saying to not send emails, letters, or tweets. But the odds of having your reps hear what you think is higher with calling them
Also, please be an engaged citizen beyond just the federal level, too. What happens in your community and the state level is crucial, too
Remember that you have the right to exercise your First Amendment rights, and don't let anyone take that away from you, no matter what
These 4 years are going to be testing for a lot of us. Don't get complacent - be ready to resist on basically every front. #Inauguration

So today when I was chatting with someone he noted how I seemed basically resigned to getting interrupted by other people in conversation, and something about that has just struck a chord with me I wasn't expecting it to

There were a few people around who randomly hijacked my conversation with this guy to say nothing of substance, and he kept bringing it back to, "and you were saying..." which I kept stumbling on because I kept forgetting what I was saying beforehand

And I just realized this has been a pattern throughout a lot of my friendships, and something I just tolerated because I felt like I had to. Like what I had to say didn't really matter, because well, if it did, why would I be getting constantly interrupted?

But I think this is another case of actions speaking louder than words. So many people can say the right things and make it seem like they get it, but you really learn about a person when you judge their behaviors towards you over the long term

I've finally accepted I've mostly had a lot of crappy friendships that ultimately hurt me and let me down when I was at my most vulnerable. It sucks. I felt responsible for it for so long, or that I couldn't engage with those people like I was "supposed" to

But I'm done blaming myself and engaging with those people. There are people out there that want to be my friend and to genuinely listen to what I have to say. I can stream and speak my mind without fear, where viewers will be entertained by what I say and do

I'm holding people to higher standards going forward to be involved in my life. I'd rather have quality over quantity, and to gracefully let those who have proven to be unhealthy through repeated behavior go. Life's too short for anything less, honestly

Anyway, long thread over. Keep quality people in your life, and don't settle for less than you deserve! Know that you can always look for better if you find your unhappy in your current situation, whether it be socially or otherwise

The cold, depressing truth is that Trump resonated with people, way beyond what traditional politics could ever have expected
The best I could get anyone I talked to about Hillary was "Well, she's not Trump." Not many were enthusiastic about her for various reasons
If you're gonna blame turnout, this isn't about third parties. It's about the Voting Rights Act gutted for the first election in 50 years
I heard stories of people down south who had to wait hours in line just to vote. Poor people, PoC, disabled people, etc. just can't do that
We need to have voting be a fundamental right, and not this thing you can do for 14 hours on a Tuesday with endless restrictions
But we have states trying to restrict voter turnout with voter ID laws, reduced times to register to vote, and guess what? It's worked.
Change starts at the local level. Republicans have control of many states and local governments, and have managed to implement this stuff
It'll be tough to fight back, I know. But we need to carry on Bernie's message and grassroots organize despite what's happened
I dunno, I've got a bunch of other opinions about this crap, but I'll save them for another time.

So, this is just a random aside, but I gotta say that over the past couple of weeks, I've felt free to be authentically myself, and it's been wonderful. After being under a depressive spell for so long, getting out of the worst of the drowning was essential.

If there's one thing I've learned that can really screw with depression, it's acting against your core values. A lot of this most recent depressive spell was related to me doing just that for the sake of others. Spoiler: this is a terrible life choice

By being removed from a toxic situation where I did just that, lo and behold, my depression eased up a lot. I was in denial about what the source of the problem was, but deep down I knew what the cause was, and it ended up gnawing me apart when I would try and deny it

Denial is a hell of a drug, but it was only getting past that denial that allowed me to heal from the psychological wounds that were wearing me down. And realizing what went wrong, I felt horribly guilty that I stayed in the situation I was in for so long, just... floundering

I derailed to a point of utter shame, all for the sake of placating someone else (and doing said placating poorly, to boot). And it was all for... nothing. I guess it was a learning experience as to what to not do, but never give up your true values for the sake of someone else

It's why I don't buy that depression is always just a chemical imbalance in your brain. This case was almost entirely circumstantial due to the toxic situation I had around me. All a drug would have done was numb me to the situation rather than fix the true source of the problem

I dunno. Just don't be afraid to be yourself, and if anyone tries to manipulate you or stop that, don't keep them in your life. Your life is too valuable to have it be derailed by people who (even if they have good intentions, my biggest judgment error) make you utterly miserable

Remember your core values, and be sure to act on them as you see fit. Care about the people you keep in your life deeply and try to be the best person you can be for them. But also don't be afraid of change. Stagnation is the enemy of growth, and nothing will last forever, anyway
